segments.text: have to make sure it's going first mr. Fowler like to have you tell us something about your early life including the the names of your parents the dates of their birth and death the places where they were born and the place where you were born and where you went to school before you went to A&M
Well, my father was William Edward Fowler, and he was a physician and lived in Huntsville, where I was reared.
And my mother was named Georgie Corbin McClanahan, and she was from a little town outside of Temple, Texas, Ohinoville.
My mother died in 1911 and my father in 1936.
And I, as I said, I was reared in Huntsville and went through the public schools and graduated from the Huntsville High School in 1916.
And from Huntsville High School then the following fall you went directly to A&M?
That's right.
What was the procedure for getting into school at A&M at that point?
I went over during the summer with some other boys and registered and Huntsville High School is a very small school and fortunately we had, we didn't have a bunch of electives and we had a necessary
credits to get in.
So you kind of pre-registered then before the school started?
Yes.
Were you at that point assigned to a military company?
I don't remember that.
I don't believe so.
I think we chose that after we went back to school.
Did you have some choice in the company that you went to?
Yes.
I had a friend who had been in B-2nd and
I tried and did get into that company.
You said you had some friends who went over there with you.
Was it the acquaintance with people who had gone to A&M before that led you to go to school there?
I don't know.
A&M just always seemed the place to go for me.
Well, you were very close to it in Huntsville.
That's right.
Of course, then that was a pretty tedious deal to get there.
You had to travel on the plane, go down to Conroe and over to Hearn, I believe it was, and then back to college.
Kind of almost all the way around Robbinsborn.
You sure were.
Let's see, Huntsville's only about 30 miles away.
No, no, it's about 80 or 90 miles.
From college.
From college.
I was thinking Huntsville was closer than that.
I think I'm correct about that, I'm not sure.
But you had to go, actually when you were going to Conroe, you were going away from College Station, weren't you?
Yes.
And then over to Hearn, and then back down to College Station.
What was your first reaction to the school and to the community of College Station when you arrived there?
Oh, I liked it from the very first.
Had you been to the campus prior to the time you went there to register?
No.
You hadn't gone there to any ball games or anything like that?
No.
Was there someone there to meet the train to sort of help you get from the train station to the college?
Or did you have to find your own way?
I don't remember.

Could you describe a typical day while you were a student, including the things of what time you got up and how you were awakened and how many hours you spent in class and what other things you did in the day besides class and what was the procedure for going to bed?
Well, they blew revelry of course on that.

big law on that campus foghorn out there by the flagpole and then we had calisthenics drill and then went to breakfast and most of our theory classes were in the mornings and the labs were in the afternoons and then we had
study hours at night with a sentinel walk in the halls, and I believe Capps was at 10 o'clock or something like that.
Did you have the sentinel the whole four years you were there, or was there a change somewhere during the time?
I believe they had that system the whole four years.
Do you recall, you mentioned that the bugle was blown at the flagpole.
Where was the flagpole located at that point?
Same place it is.
On the old military walk in front of the main building.
In front of the main building.
At one time, we have a picture of the campus that I'm not sure it's dated, but the flag pulled out in the middle of the drill field.
No.
That would make it a little further away.
Do you remember the dormitories you lived in?
Well, I was a freshman in Leggett Hall, and then I lived in Mitchell.
across the Military Walk one year and the last two years I was in Goodwin.
Those were all I believe fairly new dormitories at the time were they not?
Yes.
So they all had pretty good bathroom facilities in each of the buildings as opposed to something like Ross Hall which I believe had them only on one floor.
I was surprised the main building
was only about two years old when I went over there.
And of course, I didn't realize that until much later.
We just assumed it had been there always, you know.
Yeah, I believe the original one burned about two years before, well, about four years before you came.
Yeah, I think this one was completed in 14 or something like that.
And you wouldn't believe the price.
Well, I might.
I've seen what some of the other buildings cost.
Today it costs us a good bit more to go in and air condition some of those buildings that we built 50 years ago.
It costs them more to air condition them than it did to build them.
What was life like in those dormitories?
Was it pretty quiet or did it get pretty rambunctious at times?
Oh, we had some fun once in a while, but in general, it was pretty quiet.
What sort of thing did you do for fun in the dormitory?
Well, you might put a pan of water over a guy's door so when he opened the door, it'd fall on his head or something like that, about the extent of it.
Did you ever dump water on him when he was in bed?
No.
No?
Drowned him out?
Did you have much to complain about the food?
No.
It was all pretty good?
Yes.
Was there much variety, or did you have pretty much the same thing each day of each week?
I don't remember.
Any particular meals that you remember?
No.
I have a couple people that mentioned that they had steak every Thursday.
Mm-hmm.
We did have steaks occasionally, but I don't remember just what days.
Did the upperclassmen enjoy certain privileges that the freshmen did not have?
Yes.
What kinds of things could they do?
Well, I remember it was very difficult for a freshman to get off the campus on the weekend.
but the upperclassmen could go to Brian.
Any other things that the upperclassmen could do?
I don't remember anything particularly.
We had to learn their names and speak to them and call them by name.
Of course, there weren't so many of them.
Did you have to call them by name each time you saw them?
Yes, you're supposed to.
Well, at a later date, I remember when I visited A&M campus
When I was an undergraduate at Texas Lutheran, every stranger on campus was greeted by every Aggie he encountered, but I didn't remember hearing the Aggies greet each other by names.
They used the same greeting for Aggies as they did for visitors, as I recall.
What sorts of things did you have to do for the upperclassmen when you were a freshman?
I don't recall anything particularly.
I did a lot of work on the Longhorn and the battalion for some of the upperclassmen who were on the staffs.
Would this have been primarily in the line of artwork?
Yes.
Well, I was wondering, some of the people have indicated they frequently had to run errands for some of the upperclassmen.
would have to sometimes carry their clothes over to the laundry and things of that nature.
No.
You don't remember having to do much of that.
Some people have said they made beds and things like that, shine shoes and cleaned rifles.
No.
You missed out on all those.
Yeah.
Was there any way that a visitor to the campus could visually distinguish between members of a particular class?
In other words, was there something that identified a freshman or a sophomore or a junior or senior?
Quite obviously, they had various military ranks.
Other than that, I don't recall.
You don't recall.
OK.
sorts of things did the students do for entertainment or recreation during the times when, say, they were not in class or if they couldn't go to Bryan for one reason or another?
They had a picture show for the freshmen or any of the students every Saturday night in the old air dome.
It was covered, but the sides were open.
And they had a picture show over there every night, every Saturday night.
Was this a free picture show?
Yes.
What sorts of movies did they run generally?
Most anything that was available?
I imagine so.
Fairly current movies, or did they... Oh, we didn't know what was current.
It was just something to do then.
But primarily the freshmen would go to that because I think they were not allowed off campus after five or something like that on Saturdays.
Could I tell you a little incident about that that was real funny?
Certainly.
Streaking on A&M campus back that far, would you believe that?
We were painting the scenery for the senior class play in 20, and we got behind and had to work one Saturday night.
And, of course, you have to let the freshmen go to the picture show, and a shower came up during the show, and I went over and cornered my crew
and told them to get on down to the basement of Guyon Hall.
And they said, well, it's raining.
We don't have our raincoats.
And I said, well, that's your problem, and went on down the military walk in my slicker.
In a few minutes, across the corner of the drill field, there was a big flash of lightning.
And it looked like a bunch of Greek white marble statues, these boys running.
They had stripped off every bit of their clothing, rolled it up, and put it under their hats.
When I got the guy in Hall's basement, they were putting on their dry clothes ready to paint.
Well, that showed a little bit of ingenuity.
Yes.
But you mentioned painting the scenery for the senior class play.
Yes.
Was that during your senior year?
Yes, that was it.
Do you remember what the play was?
No, I don't.
Was that a regular custom that the senior class put on a play?
Yes.
Did they charge admission then to the students, or was it a free performance?
Gee, I don't remember.
We took it over to Brian, I know, and had some performances over there.
Well, I was interested in that.
No one else had ever mentioned to me that the senior class had put on a play.
Were there any other performances of that type that were
put on during the year that students could go to, say other than the picture show and the senior class play?
Did any of the other classes put on a play?
I don't think so.
Were there any outside people coming in to lecture or things of that nature?
We didn't have very much of that back then.
Did you go to the YMCA to play games or anything of that sort?
Oh yes.
What sorts of games did you play over there?
Well I believe we had pool and of course Casey's Confectionery was in the basement over there and it was quite a hangout place if you had 15 cents for a molded milk.
At one point there was a swimming pool in the basement of the Y.
Was that there when you were there or was that later?
I don't recall that.
Because I think the Y must have been fairly new when you were there.
Was that in about 1914 or something like that when it was opened?
I noticed you attained ultimately the rank of second lieutenant.
Did the officers in the Corps enjoy any particular privileges that were not available to the regular students?
As far as I know, they had a staff table in the dining hall for the regimental staff.
But the cadet officers ate with their companies.
So it would just be, but they had the same, the regimental officers had the same food.
Yes.
Except they just didn't have any freshmen at their table.
Yeah, that's right.
Okay.
Did you have any favorite teachers or instructors when you were at A&M?
I don't believe so.
I think your field was architecture.
Was Ernest Langford
there at all when you were there?
I don't believe he was there.
I have known him since very well.
I hope you get a chance you'll give him a call.
Oh, I certainly will.
He was my predecessor as archivist.
Yes, I know.
And so I'll certainly try to give him a call and give him your regards.
I'd appreciate that.
What sort of feelings did the students have towards the administration of the school?
And I think there was a dual kind of administration with President Bazell, more or less in charge of the academic end of it, and the commandant of the bull in charge of the military end.
That's right.
Did the students think pretty highly of both of these people?
I think so.
Who was the commandant when you were there?
Bull Muller.
Muller?
Muller.
Now how would you spell that?
M-U-E-L-L-E-R, I believe.
And then Ike Ashman was there at the later years.
I gather he was a fairly popular...
Very, very popular.
I was fortunate that I belonged to a little club they called the Junta.
there.

A few faculty members organized this and then they each selected one senior cadet and they each member presented a paper sometime during the year but they were men like Ike Ashburn and D. X. Bible and Tommy Mayo the librarian, Mr. Thomas from the English department
and so forth.
I appreciated getting to know those men.
So you had this junta, or club, was made up of half faculty and half senior students?
Yes, each faculty member invited one cadet.
You might ask McQuillan about that, he was a member.
Did the students as well as the faculty members present papers?
Yes, on any subject you chose.
It didn't have to be the field in which you were majoring.
No.
Do you have any recollection of what you presented a paper on?
Yes, I do.
I presented a paper on the characteristics of a people as revealed in their monumental architecture.
Of course, if you study it enough,
practically reveals every facet of their lives, political, religious, social, and everything.
From what I have learned of Dr. Mayo since I've been at A&M, I gather that must have been a kind of paper that would have interested him.
In his later life, at least, he was interested in the cycles between romantic and realistic in art and architecture and literature.
He was quite a brilliant man.
Anything I have heard about him indicates that that was the case.
Do you remember anything about the customs or traditions which were in existence when you were there?
We know there was some amount of hazing
things of that nature.
Was there a bonfire for the University of Texas football game or for any other football game that you remember?
I don't remember about that.
What about a muster on 21st of April?
I don't recall that on the campus either.
Well, that's sort of a big day today, currently I should say.
Were there any girls in any of the classes that you attended?
No, there were one or two girls who were daughters of professors that went to classes, but I was not in a class with one of them.
Do you remember who the girls were?
No.
Okay.
We know that at least a portion of the students who were on campus when you were there had employment of one type or other.
Did you have any employment while you were at school?
Yes, I did.
When I was a freshman, I worked student labor in the Department of Drawing for Scripp Mitchell and I
filed and recorded grades on drawings.
15 cents an hour.
About how many hours did you put in in a week?
No, not many.
Architecture requires a gradient of time from a student.
So there's Mr. Mitchell, you called him script.
He would grade the drawings.
Yes, and then I would record the grades in his record books and then file the drawings as they were returned to the students at the end of this.
So you had a separate file for each student then, I take it?
I don't know how we did it exactly, or classes anyway.
At the end of the year, the student would get all of these drawings back?
Yes.
Did you have any other?
I also worked for the Extension Department making charts and graphs, you know, or circle divided into segments, different percentage.
And I was really going good on that there by the time I graduated.
They were paying me 50 cents an hour for it, and I was getting students to do it for 25, 10 cents over their student rate.
And I remember at the Dallas Fair, I think we did about $40 worth of work.
That was a big deal.
This was for the Agricultural Extension Service there?
Yes.
or any other things that you can recall along that line that you did?
No, I don't think so.
Did you work for the, I take it you worked for the Extension Service for what, more than one year?
Yes.
Oh, we started out making, you know, like plans of a pig feeding crawl for a chicken deal or something.
This would be for some of the, this would be some of the bullet, that they use these illustrations in some of the bulletins, uh-huh.
Okay.
Did the students who participated in athletics, like on the college football team or the basketball team, have any privileges that normal, regular students didn't enjoy?
Not that I know of.
A couple of people have said they knew that they had a training table.
Well, I know they had that.
They ate.
But I don't know what they ate.
Do you know Henry Harrison over in Bryan?
Doctor?
Veterinarian?
No.
He's one of my classmates.
He was on the football team.
I believe Huron Allen mentioned him.
He had some pictures of a 1919 football team.
He mentioned Chick Harrison, I believe he was called.
That's the boy.
Oh, another job I had was, I believe it was a custom that the team that won the game got to kept the
to keep the football they were playing with at the end of the game.
And for the athletic department, we put the game and the score on those footballs, and I did that for a while.
You did that.
I have a couple of those footballs in the archives.
One is the 1939 National Championship
ball and it's signed by I think everybody who played on the team and it has to score.

See I believe they played Tulane I believe in that game and I have that one and I believe I have another one when we beat the University of Texas and pointed to nothing I believe in that score is on there.
Of course I was down there when we had those two years of
I believe we were unscored on for two whole years.
I believe so.
In 1917 and 1919, the football team was unscored on.
One of the things which happened while you were there was this incident of some Aggies going over to Austin to brand their longhorn steer.
Did you have any knowledge about that?
Not until it was all over.

Along the same line, we have some indication in the archives that this same steer was later butchered and they had a banquet over at Austin to which some people from A&M and some people from Austin were invited.
Did you have any indication of this while you were studying?
No.
We have reason to believe that it was in January of 1920
We have a copy of an invitation to it, but we haven't found out anything else about it.
Did you have any opportunity to participate in either the First or the Second World War?
I only belonged to the Students Army Training Corps that they had there at college.
And that was during, what, your junior year?
Yes.
Actually, it was only the fall part of 1918, I guess, and you were discharged and enrolled in regular school again in January.
Yes, we were discharged in December of that year.
And then by the time the second one rolled around while you were
Overage is for me.
Not quite overage, but I did construction work principally under the Corps of Engineers.
So you were sort of a civilian employee for the Corps of Engineers.
Well, not for contractors who were working for them.
It was sort of a necessary defense job.
Yeah, we did the Longhorn Ordnance Plant over on Caddo Lake,
And then I went up to Canada and I was at Whitehorse for about a year on the building the pipeline up there.
Let's see, I noticed that according to your Longhorn in 1920, you were in Bee Company the second
regiment here as a fish, and then you switched to E Company.
Was that a fairly common practice, switching from company to company?
Well, I was probably one of the least military men on the campus, or that's ever been there, and I think they were glad to get me out and be second.
It was a real fine military company.
Uh-huh.
So what did they... Well, E was good, but I mean they weren't
They were a little bit more run-of-the-mill.
I gather there was a pretty fierce competition between the companies, was there not?
Yes.
For outstanding grades or what have you in drill.
So did you request a switch to E or did somebody request that for you?
I don't remember.
